Create Your First ScrollTrigger Animation

So far, you’ve seen how GSAP can bring life to your website with .to(), .from(), and .fromTo() animations.

But here’s the thing: Animations that play automatically are great but wouldn’t it be even cooler if your animations react to scrolling ? That’s where ScrollTrigger comes in. It lets you create dynamic, scroll-powered animations that feel alive and interactive.

Today, you’ll create your very first scroll-controlled animation, a simple elegant starting point for endless scroll-based magic.

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/all";

gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);

gsap.to(".box", {
x: 500,
rotate: 360,
duration: 3,
ease: "power2.out",
scrollTrigger: {
trigger: ".box",
start: "top center",
markers: true,
},
});

Result

The HTML Structure

Let’s start with a simple structure to work with:

<section class="spacer">Scroll down to see the animation</section>
<div class="box"></div>
<section class="spacer">
    Box moves when start hits the starter-marker
</section>

Starting off, we’ve got our HTML, super simple. We’ve got two <section> tags with the class spacer, and a <div> with the class box in the middle.
The idea is that these spacer sections give us enough scrollable area so that we can actually trigger the animation when the .box comes into view. The .box is the star of the show, it’s the element we’ll animate.

CSS for the Setup

body {
  font-family: sans-serif;
  margin: 0;
  background: #0e0e0e;
  color: #f0f0f0;
  padding: 0% 50px;
  overflow-x: hidden;
}

.spacer {
  height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  font-size: 1.5rem;
}

.box {
  width: 150px;
  height: 150px;
  background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0ae448, #00bae2);
  border-radius: 20px;
  box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(99, 241, 142, 0.5);
}

For the CSS, we’ve kept it simple: the .spacer sections are full-screen with 100vh height, giving us enough scroll space to trigger the animation.
We also added overflow-x: hidden on the body so when the .box moves 500px to the right, we won’t get an ugly horizontal scrollbar popping up. And of course, some styling on the .box itself to make it stand out. Simple, clean, and functional!

Our GSAP Animation

Now, let's talk about the animation.
We’re using gsap.to(), which lets us animate a target element, in this case, .box to new properties.

import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

gsap.to(".box", {
  x: 500,
  rotate: 360,
  duration: 3,
  ease: "power2.out",
});
Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

gsap.to(".box", {
x: 500,
rotate: 360,
duration: 3,
ease: "power2.out",
});

Result

Here’s what we’re telling it to do:

PropertyWhat it does
x: 500Means we want to move it 500 pixels to the right.
rotate: 360Will make it spin a full 360 degrees.
duration: 3Says this animation will take 3 seconds to complete.
ease: "power2.out"Gives it a natural, smooth deceleration at the end, so it doesn’t just stop abruptly.

So that’s our basic animation: the .box will smoothly slide to the right and spin around. The problem is Our Animation is already finished when we arrive the second section !

🤔 What if we want this animation to trigger only when we scroll to it ?

Right now, our animation kicks in as soon as the page loads. But as you noticed, by the time we scroll down to the second section, the animation has already played out, and that’s not very exciting!

So what if we want the animation to wait and only happen when the .box actually enters the viewport? That’s where GSAP’s ScrollTrigger plugin comes in. It lets us control our animations based on how far we’ve scrolled on the page.

Let’s take a look at how to plug it in and make our animation start only when we scroll to that .box.

ScrollTrigger integration

Alright, so let’s bring ScrollTrigger into the mix and see how it makes our animation respond to scroll!

First, because ScrollTrigger is an extra plugin for GSAP, we need to register it.

Warning

This is super important !
Without registering the plugin, GSAP won’t know about it, and you’ll wonder why nothing’s working!

Here’s what we’re adding at the top of our JavaScript:

import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/all";
gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);
This tells GSAP, Hey, we’re using ScrollTrigger in this project , make it available!

Next, let’s see how we can add ScrollTrigger to our existing animation. We already have our .to() animation for the .box, and now we’re just going to add a ScrollTrigger object inside:

gsap.to(".box", {
  x: 500,
  rotate: 360,
  duration: 3,
  ease: "power2.out",
  scrollTrigger: {
    trigger: ".box",
    start: "top center",
    markers: true,
  },
});

So what’s happening here?

PropertyWhat it does
trigger: ".box"We’re telling ScrollTrigger, ‘Watch the .box element to decide when to start the animation.’
start: "top center"Means, ‘When the top of the .box hits the center of the viewport, that’s the moment to begin the animation.’
markers: trueThis shows little start and end markers right on the screen, so you can see exactly where your trigger points are. Super helpful for debugging!

And with these few lines, our animation now waits for the .box to scroll into view before it starts. So as you scroll down, you’ll see the .box smoothly move to the right and spin around right when it enters the center of your screen, not a moment before.

That’s the magic of ScrollTrigger ! It takes our normal GSAP animations and makes them interactive, giving your site a dynamic, engaging feel that responds to the user’s scrolling.

Code Playground
import "./styles.css";
import gsap from "gsap";

import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/all";

gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);

gsap.to(".box", {
x: 500,
rotate: 360,
duration: 3,
ease: "power2.out",
scrollTrigger: {
trigger: ".box",
start: "top center",
markers: true,
},
});

Result

Understanding the start and end Properties

Two of the most important properties in ScrollTrigger are start and end. These define exactly when your animation begins and ends in relation to the viewport and the trigger element.

start Property

This defines when the animation should begin. It’s written as a string like "top center", "bottom top", etc., and combines two parts:

  • First part : relates to the trigger element (top, center, bottom).
  • Second part : relates to the viewport (top, center, bottom).

For example: start: "top center" means “start the animation when the top of the trigger element hits the center of the viewport.”

end Property

This defines when the animation should finish. It follows the same structure as start. If you don’t set end, ScrollTrigger won’t know when to finish scrubbed animations (or to end the trigger state for pinning, etc.) - which will be in the next two lessons.

Example: end: "bottom 20%" means “end the animation when the bottom of the trigger element hits 20% from the top of the viewport.”

For simple one-time animations (like our .to() example), start is often enough. But for scroll-synced effects or pinning, you’ll want to define both start and end to fine-tune exactly when things should happen.

And that’s it! You’ve created your first scroll-triggered animation with GSAP and ScrollTrigger. In the next lesson, we’ll build on this to create more complex, interactive animations!
